<div id="review_4088662377" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4088662377" />
    <a title="John" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11238434-john"><img alt="John" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442515412p2/11238434.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4088662377?book_show_action=true">Jul 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John" href="/user/show/11238434-john">John</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/24000470-the-warhound-and-the-world-s-pain">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4088662377" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7897539664914989887">Excellent, certainly one of Moorcock&apos;s best. While the von Bek sequence is not the most well known of MMs work, it is very much worth reading. More based in the &apos;real world&apos; than his earlier fantasies, WH&amp;WP introduces Ulrich von Bek who does the Devil&apos;s Work. An intriguing premise that later writers (I&apos;m looking at you, Ennis and Gaiman) took a paragraph from and expanded into entire sagas. Not perfect, as ever: it does veer into his standard random picaresque encounters and chase scene sequenc</span>
  <span id="freeText7897539664914989887" style="display:none">Excellent, certainly one of Moorcock's best. While the von Bek sequence is not the most well known of MMs work, it is very much worth reading. More based in the 'real world' than his earlier fantasies, WH&amp;WP introduces Ulrich von Bek who does the Devil's Work. An intriguing premise that later writers (I'm looking at you, Ennis and Gaiman) took a paragraph from and expanded into entire sagas. Not perfect, as ever: it does veer into his standard random picaresque encounters and chase scene sequences toward the end and his portrayal of Sabrina is irritatingly stereotypical (period tropes is a reason, but not an excuse). Nevertheless a fine metaphysical romp. I seem to recall 'City and the Autumn Stars' (the next in the loose sequence) being pretty good too. Entertainingly (for the nerds) there's a character called Philander Groot who actually says 'I am Groot' at one point. Ha.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7897539664914989887" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


