<div id="review_2032061958" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2032061958" />
    <a title="Venetia Green" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8270722-venetia-green"><img alt="Venetia Green" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1338466405p2/8270722.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2032061958?book_show_action=true">Jun 30, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Venetia Green" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Venetia Green" href="/user/show/8270722-venetia-green">Venetia Green</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780671437084" href="/book/show/399384.The_War_Hound_and_the_World_s_Pain">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2032061958" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5559991696457926467">Michael Moorcock echoes the form and picareque adventures of medieval romances in this short and fast moving novel. It opens in the mode of historical fiction, set in German lands during the upheavals of the Thirty Years War; but the novel soon steps into the realms of the fantastic. I would hesitate to label it &apos;fantasy&apos;. It is a medieval-style romance set at the end of the age of superstition and heralds the beginning of the Age of Reason. <br/>True to the form of such romance, many threads are lef</span>
  <span id="freeText5559991696457926467" style="display:none">Michael Moorcock echoes the form and picareque adventures of medieval romances in this short and fast moving novel. It opens in the mode of historical fiction, set in German lands during the upheavals of the Thirty Years War; but the novel soon steps into the realms of the fantastic. I would hesitate to label it 'fantasy'. It is a medieval-style romance set at the end of the age of superstition and heralds the beginning of the Age of Reason. <br />True to the form of such romance, many threads are left untied. Marvels simply appear and then disappear, unexplained. What is the Wildgrave's backstory and what happens to him in the end? Why is the dragon wounded in one leg? In any ordinary tale, these untied threads would be faults. Moorcock has excused himself by virtue of the form he adopts.<br />The outstanding aspect of this novel, however, was the philosophical conundrums it posed. Von Bek must consider the very meanings of life, of good and evil, of heaven and hell. He meets Lucifer and takes a tour through hell. Nothing is as expected. All of it is thought provoking. </span>
  <a data-text-id="5559991696457926467" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

